<BlogLayout
  title="Why Ko-fi (And How Your Support Actually Gets Used) — 3D3D Blog"
  description="Full transparency on why 3D3D uses Ko-fi for support, where the money goes, and why we chose it over Patreon or other platforms."
  datePublished="2026-02-25"
  author="Ken"
>
  <h2>The Short Answer</h2>

  <p>
    Ko-fi takes zero platform fees on donations. Patreon takes up to 12%. For a small operation like 3D3D, that difference matters. Every dollar someone sends us should go toward filament, hardware, and getting this project further down the road — not toward a platform's overhead.
  </p>

  <p>
    That's the practical reason. But there's a philosophical one too: I don't want to run a subscription content business. Patreon's model is built around locking content behind tiers, dripping out exclusives, managing a membership. That's a full-time job by itself and it's not the job I want.
  </p>

  <p>
    Ko-fi lets people support us when they want, for whatever amount they want, with no obligation and no locked content. You buy us a coffee, we put that money to work. Simple.
  </p>

  <h2>Where the Money Actually Goes</h2>

  <p>
    I believe in being transparent about this. Here's the breakdown of how support funds get used:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Filament and materials (about 40%):</strong> Engineering-grade filament isn't cheap. A single roll of PA-CF costs $50-80. PPA-CF is more. The Newport Bermuda campaign alone will consume dozens of rolls in testing and final parts</li>
    <li><strong>Hardware and maintenance (about 25%):</strong> Nozzles wear out. Belts stretch. Build plates need replacing. Printers are tools and tools need upkeep. This also covers replacement parts and upgrades that improve output quality</li>
    <li><strong>Shipping and logistics (about 20%):</strong> Getting printers to event locations, shipping parts to marine clients, moving equipment for the campaign. Fuel, postage, packaging — it adds up fast in Atlantic Canada where distances are long</li>
    <li><strong>Software and services (about 15%):</strong> CAD subscriptions, slicing software licenses, web hosting, domain renewals. The unsexy stuff that keeps the operation running</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Zero percent goes to salary. This isn't my day job yet. Every dollar of support goes directly into making the project better, not into my pocket.
  </p>

  <h2>Why Not Patreon</h2>

  <p>
    I've thought about it. Patreon has better discovery and a bigger user base. But three things keep me away:
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Fees.</strong> Patreon's cut is 5-12% depending on your plan, plus payment processing. On a $5 contribution, the creator might see $3.80. Ko-fi passes through the full amount minus only the payment processor's standard fee.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Content pressure.</strong> Patreon works best when you're producing exclusive content on a schedule — behind-the-scenes videos, early access, patron-only posts. I'd rather put my time into printing parts and building things. The blog, the videos, the project updates — those are free for everyone. I'm not going to paywall a build log.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Simplicity.</strong> Ko-fi is straightforward. There's a page, there's a button, you support if you want to. No tier management, no reward fulfillment, no membership drama. I've seen creators burn out managing their Patreon community while their actual project stalls. That's not a trap I want to walk into.
  </p>

  <h2>What Your Support Makes Possible</h2>

  <p>
    Let me give you some concrete examples from the last few months:
  </p>

  <p>
    A $20 contribution bought two rolls of PETG that I used to prototype a custom winch handle adapter for the Newport Bermuda boat. That part went through three revisions before we got the geometry right. Three rolls of filament, a week of testing, one final part that works perfectly.
  </p>

  <p>
    A $50 contribution covered the cost of a hardened steel nozzle that replaced a worn-out one on our primary production printer. That nozzle will run for another six months of carbon fibre printing before it needs replacing.
  </p>

  <p>
    A $10 contribution paid for the packaging materials to ship a set of custom clips to a marine client in Newfoundland. Small amount, real impact.
  </p>

  <h2>The Bigger Picture</h2>

  <p>
    3D3D is a small operation doing real work. We're not venture-funded. We don't have corporate sponsors. We're building this on skill, stubbornness, and the support of people who think what we're doing matters.
  </p>

  <p>
    If you've ever used a 3D-printed part on your boat, your car, or in your shop and thought "this is actually useful" — that's the feeling we're trying to spread. Your support on Ko-fi helps us do more of it, faster, for more people.
  </p>

  <p>
    And if you can't support financially, that's fine too. Share the blog, tell a friend about 3D3D, send us your broken part and let us show you what's possible. That's support too.
  </p>
</BlogLayout>
